@realmoney Sep 26, 2019 | 04:37 PM EDT DOUG KASS 不怕慢, 就怕停 Wise Words to End the Day: Be Not Afraid of Growing Slowly "May you live in interesting times" is an English expression purported to be a translation of a traditional Chinese curse.

How appropriate is this quote during these times of uncertainty? There are several phrases on the concept of uncertainty that I have often repeated in my Diary: 1. "The only certainty is the lack of certainty." 2. "Never in my investing lifetime have I seen so many possible

social, economic, political, geopolitical and market outcomes - many of them uncertain." 3. "With such uncertainty, are we as safe, as citizens and investors, as the market presumes?"* It should be no wonder I recoil at those (in the financial media) that confidently sell their

ideas and opinions with little follow-up of the investment boners. Today's market influences were straight forward. *All week I have made the points that the impeachment hearings will likely have adverse ramifications a. for trade discussions between the U.S. and China

(that's likely to be growth unfriendly), b. assist mightily in the continued advance in U.S. Sen. Elizabeth Warren's -- now leading -- position in the polls (and that's market unfriendly) c. eliminate the likelihood of passage any possible fiscal or growth policy initiatives

that require bipartisan support (again that, too, is growth unfriendly). * The Peleton (PTON) IPO's failure (following the WeWork fiasco) puts pressure on "growthy," disruptive and/or conceptual stocks (that's market unfriendly). I will end the day with another Chinese quote .

that has some relevance to today's markets: "Be not afraid of growing slowly." I end the day in market-neutral exposure -- with the expectation that my portfolio may be growing slowly. @tomkeene @riskreversal @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @lizclaman @terranovajoe @GuyAdami
